  "<b>Part 2: Characteristics of Each Season</b>:<br><br>To help students understand the seasons more effectively, it's helpful to display pictures or illustrations representing each season. The visual aids can enhance their learning and help them associate specific characteristics with each time of year. Here are some details about the appearance of each season:<br><br><b>Spring:</b><br>Flowers bloom (e.g., daisies, tulips).<br>Trees grow new leaves.<br>Animals (e.g., lambs, birds) are born and start to grow.<br>Days become longer, and temperatures rise.<br><br><b>Summer:</b><br>Trees have full, green leaves.<br>Flowers are in full bloom.<br>Days are long, and the weather is warm to hot.<br>Animals are active and many are in their full-grown state.<br><br><b>Autumn (Fall):</b><br>Leaves turn orange, yellow, and red before falling.<br>Crops are harvested.<br>Days grow shorter, and the weather cools down.<br>Animals prepare for winter (e.g., squirrels gather food, some animals begin to hibernate).<br><br><b>Winter:</b><br>Snow may cover the ground in colder regions.<br>Many trees lose their leaves.<br>Animals like bears hibernate, and others adapt to the cold (e.g., growing thicker fur).<br>Days are short, and the weather is cold, often below freezing.",
  
